{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_kale_ver01/data/sn91068749/0027955811A/1948122801/0959.xml":{"full_text":"Today's Top\nRadio Shows\nThe beet radio programs\u2014\nthose with nationwide audiences\n\u2014are printed in the Herald\u2019s\ndaily schedules.\nBy listing all the nearby sta\ntions, the Herald gives its five\ncounty readers a choice of sev\neral stations carrying their fav\norite programs.\nNBC: wTAPt\u2014700 kilocycles\u2014.\nNorfolk; WPTF\u2014880\u2014Raleigh;\nWMBC7\u20141350\u2014Richmond.\nCBS: WRVA\u20141140\u2014Richmond\nABC: WGH\u20141340\u2014Norfolk;\nWGH\u20141340- -Norfolk; WNAO\u2014\n850\u2014Raleigh- WRNL\u2014910\u2014\nRichmond.\nMBS: WCBT 1230\u2014Roanoke\nRapids; WSAP-1400\u2014Norfolk:\nWRAL\u20141240\u2014Raleigh; WLEE\u2014\n1450\u2014Richmond.\nNew York, Dec. 28\u2014(AP)\nTelevision expects to get in on\nat least four of the bowl games\nthat are being broadcast coast\nto coast on New Year\u2019s. How*\never, the telecasts will be pri\nmarily on a local basis.\nSomething ambitious is plann\ned for the Orange Bowl at Mia\nmi, Fla. first telecast of this\nevent, it will be put on an 18 by\n24-foot screen in an auditorium\naccommodating 2.300 persons.\nSpecial equipment, including\nfive cameras, is being set up by\nthe RCA television barnstorm\ning unit to make the stunt pos\nsible.\nAnnouncer assignments forj\nthe radio broadcasts will put\nTed Husing, former CBS sports\ndirector, on NBC.\nHusing will be at the \u2018Gator\nBowl in Jacksonville, Fla., while\nBill Sterns is to tell of the Har\nbor Bowl at San Diego, Calif. It\nwas this contest that NBC sub\nstituted for the Rose Bowl when\nit went to CBS.\nAt Husing\u2019s old spot on CBS\nfor the Orange Bowl. Red Bar\nber again will be taking care of\nthings, while Mel Allen is going\nout to California for the relay\nof the Rose Bowl, the one that\nStern used to broadcast.\nTUISDAY, DICIMBIR 21\nIvening\n:00\u2014News Report 13 Alin.\u2014nbc\nNewscast Kvery Day\u2014ebs\nNetwork Silent Hour\u2014abc-e*\u00abt\nKiddles Hour (repeat)\u2014abc-west\nNetwork Silent (1 hr.)\u2014mbs-east\nKiddles Hour (repeat)\u2014mbsweet\n:1ft\u2014Sports: Music Time\u2014nbe\nDiscussion Series-ebs\n\u2022:4ft\u2014Newscast by Three\u2014nbc\nLowell Thomas (repeat ID\u2014ebs\nTiOO\u2014Supper Club\u2014nbc-basic\nThe Beulsh Skit\u2014ebs\nNews and Commentary\u2014abo\nFulton Lewis. Jr.\u2014mbs\n?|1\u00bb\u2014News and Comment\u2014nbc\nJack Smith Show\u2014ebs\nDaily Commentary\u2014abc\nDinner Date\u2014mbs\n7:SO\u2014Smoothies Trto\u2014 nbc\nBob Croaby Club\u2014ebs\nMueie Relaxin* Time\u2014abo\nNews Comment\u2014mbs\n7i4S\u2014News Comment\u2014nbc\nNews Broadcast\u2014ebs\nSports Comment\u2014mbs\n\u2022;06\u2014This Is Tour Life\u2014nbe\nMystery Theater Play\u2014ebs\nYouth Asks Government\u2014abo\nGeo. O'Hanlon Show\u2014mbs\n\u2022:1ft\u2014News Broadcast\u2014a be\n\u2022:SO\u2014 Date with Judy\u2014nbc\nMr. and Mrs. North\u2014ebs\nAmerica\u2019s Town Meeting\u2014abc\nDetective Drama\u2014mbs\n\u2022lift\u2014Hy Gardner Says\u2014mbs\n:00\u2014Bob Hope Show\u2014nbc\nWe the People, Guest\u2014ebs\nGabriel Heatter. Comment\u2014mbs\n:1ft\u2014News Broadcast\u2014mbs\n;30\u2014Fibber and Molly\u2014nbc\nLife with Luigi\u2014ebs\nNews Comment\u2014abc\nLone Wolf Drama\u2014mbs\n:4ft\u2014Detroit Symphony\u2014abc\n:Sft\u2014News for 5 Minutes\u2014mbs\n10:00\u2014Big Town Drama\u2014nbo\nHit the Jackpot\u2014ebs\nAmerican Forum\u2014mbs\n10:30\u2014People Are Funny\u2014nbc\nM. Amsterdam Show\u2014ebs\nLet Freedom Ring\u2014abc\nDance Orchestra\u2014mbs\n10:4ft\u2014Strings Serenade\u2014abc\n11:00\u2014News A Variety to 1\u2014nbe\nNews. Variety. 2 hrs.\u2014ebs\nNews and Dance Band\u2014abc\nNews, Dance Band 2 hrs.\u2014mbs\n1f:0O\u2014Dancing Continued\u2014abc-west\nTuning tonight: NBC\u20148 This\nis Your Life; 8:30 Date with\nJudy; 9 Bob Hope, Recording of\nBerlin show; 9:30 Fibber and\nMolly; 10:30 People are Funny.\nCBS\u20148 Mystery Theater; 8:30\nMr. and Mrs. North; 9 We the\nPeople, ^ack Banny guest, 10\nHit the Jackpot; 10:30 Morey\nAmsterdam Show.\nABC-7:30 Music Relaxin\u2019\nTime; 8:30 Town Meeting on\nWage Increases; 9:45 Detroit\nSymphony; 10:30 Let Freedom\nRing.\nMBS\u20148 Geo. 0\u2018Hanlon Skit;\n9:30 Lone Wolfe; 10, American\nForum \u201cBusiness Outlook for\n\u201949.\u201d\nHerald Will Carry Babgon\u2019g Forecagt\nFor Buginegg During 1949 Tomorrow\nThe Herald will publish Roger\nW. Babson\u2019s BUSINESS AND\nFINANCIAL OUTLOOK FOR\n1949 TOMORROW.\nWe are bringing this article to\nyour attention because we feel\nthat our readers deserve the\nbest and most accurate mater\nial available. Therefore, because\nof Mr. Babson\u2019s outstanding re\ncord for accuracy in his Annual\nForecasts we are publishing this\nfeature to help you chart your\ncourse for the coming year-.\nMr. Babson\u2019s 1949 Ooutlok willi\ncontain 50 Forecasts covering\nsuch important topics as: Gen\neral Business, Commodity Pric-i\nes, Taxes, Retail and Foreign\nTrade, Labor, Inflation, Farm\nOutlook, Stock Market, Real Es\ntate, Politics.\nRoger W. Babson\u2019s BUSINESS\nAND FINANCIAL OUTLOOK\nFOR 1949 will appear in the\nHerald on Wednesday.\nMr. Babson a pioneer In\nthe field of business and finan\ncial statistics\u2014enjoys a truly1\nremarkable record for accuracy\nin his Annual Forecasts. H i s\nscore for 1948 was 91 per cent\ncorrect.\nOn January 1, 1948 Babson\nwas the only commentator who\ndared to predict:\n1) That there would be no\nWorld War III in 1948.\n2) That \u201cdue to the bungling\nof the price controversy Mr. j\nTruman has a fair chance of re-1\nelection\u201d.\n3) That the Dow Jones In\ndustrial Averages would fluctu\nate between an upper ceiling of\naround 185 and a floor of around\n165, and that Commodity Specu\nl\u00bbtion would be curbed.\nWATCH FOR MR. BABSON'S\n1949 OUTLOOK IN OUR ISSUE\nOF TOMMORROW.\nKiwanis Club In\nScotland Neck Has\nMusical Program\nScotland Neck\u2014At the regular\nmeeting of the Kiwanis Club, Ro\nbert Shields had charge of the\nprogram which consisted of se\nveral musical selections by Mrs.\nA. O. Moore, Mrs. J. T. Madry,\nMiss Edith Bradlye, James Li\nvermon, Harry Lee Marks, Jim\nPittman, Robert Shields, W. D.\nHarden and Mrs. W. E. Goode\naccompanied them. Among the\npieces included, were several\nChristmas songs.\nDuring the business meeting\nwhich preceded the program, El\nlis Ferber reported that follow\ning the recommendation of his\ncommittee in a letter to post of\nfice officials, there was now in\nstituted in Scotland Neck parcel\npost delivery once a day.\nThe Rev. W. E. Goode, chair\nman of the charity committee,\nreported that the special pro\nject for the year was help\ning certain needy families and\nas yet the contributions were in\nadequate for the project as out\nlined. He asked those members\nwho had not yet made their do\nnations, to please do so before\nChristmas.\nWoodland College\nStudents Visit\nHomes During Holidays\nWoodland Several college\nstudents have been visiting with\ntheir families over the Christ\nmas holidays. Some of them are\nJean Elliott of Chapel Hill; Sa\nrah Bazemore, Frances Peele,\nMary Ellen Carter of East Caro\nlina Teacher\u2019s College; Betty\nGriffin and Hilda Liverman o f\nWomen\u2019s College of the Univer\nsity of North Carolina; Mary\nAnn Reece and Nancy Ray Par\nker of Guilford College; Jane\nEllen Griffin of Meredith; Jane\nDickie of Peace; Bobby Hollo\nman, W. R. Parker, Jr. and Rai\nford Futrell of Wake Forest.\nEnglish Neglect\nTheir War Medals\nLONDON (AP)- Talk about\nthe Englishman\u2019s traditional re\nserve The Royal Air Force says\nonly one person in every five\nwho are eligible to wear cam\npaign stars and war medals\nhave so far entered claims for\nem.\nthem.\nMotor Vehicles Division Announces j\nAuto Inspection Periods for 1949\nKAj_,n,iut-i,\u2014 me Motor vemc\nle Department today announced\ninspection periods for various\nmodel vehicles for the first half\nof 1949.\nThe Mechanical Inspection\nLaw, passed by the 1947 Legis\nlature, provided that all vehicles\nregistered in North Carolina be\ninspected once during 1948 and\ntwice a year there after.\nAccording to a new Inspection\nManual, released today by the\nMechanical Inspection Division\nof the Department of Motor Ve\nhicles, the first semi-annual in\nspection period for each year\nwill begin on January 1 and end\non June 30. The second semi\nannual inspection period will be\ngin on July 1 and end on Dec\nember 31.\nThe Manual sets forth the in\nspection deadlines for all vehic\nles for the first inspection per\niod as follow's:\nAll vehicles of the year model\nup to and including the year 19\n36 must be inspected by Jan\nuary 31, 1949.\nAll vehicles of 1937 and 1938\nmodels must be inspected by\nFebruary 28.\nModels 1939 and 1940 must be\ninspected by March 31.\nAll vehicles of the year mo\ndels 1941 and 1942 must be in\nspectea t>y April ju.\nModels 1943 through 1947 must!\nbe inspected by May 31.\nAll year models 1948 and 1949\nmust be inspected by June 30.\nThe Manual further states that\n\u201cthe operation of any vehicle af\nter the time limit set for inspec\ntion, without displaying the of\nficial seal of approval, will be a\nviolation of the Motor Vehicle\nLaws of 1947.\u201d\nA provision is made that be\nginning January 1. 1949, the own\ner of a vehicle will have 30 days\nfrom the date of acquisition of!\na vehicle to have it inspected, j\nprovided that pending inspection\nthe owner shall have with him\nat all times a bill of sale or\nother sufficient evidence to show\nthe date and place of acquisi- j\ntion of that vehicle.\nArthur T. Moore. Director of\nthe Mechanical Inspection Divi\ni sion, said the same type of seals,\nstickers, and tabs will be used\nj in 1949 as have been used in \u201948.\ni These include the blue seal of\ni approval in the shape of the\nj State of North Carolina; the red\n1 diamond seal for rejection of a\n.vehicle; and the large yellow\nsticker for \u201ccondemned\u201d vehic\ni les.\nMoore said that 40 inspection\nt lanes would operate full time\nWoodland\nMrs. Lawrence Denton\nCorrespondent\nWoodland Six Woodland\nnen will leave Rocky Mount to\nlav aboard the football special\nrain for New Orleans and the\nSugar Bowl football game be\nween the University of North\nCarolina and Oklahoma Univer\nsity on Saturday.\nR. C. Benthall, John G. Bur\njwyn, John S. Vaughan, R. B.\njriffin D. S. Griffin and Thom\nis Harris will be those from\nVoodland who attend the game\n'rom Woodland.\nMr. and Mrs. D. B. Herring\nind daughter, Vera of Raleigh\nDrive returned yesterday after\nhaving spent Christmas week\nend in Tampa, Fla., visiting\nMrs. Herring's mother and\nEriends.\nJoe Grzibowski, first-string\ncenter for Syracuse University,\nis No. 5 man in the varsity shell\nduring the spring.\nthroughout the State during 19\n49. He added that if motorist!\nwill cooperate by bringing theii\nvehicles to the lanes during the\ntime limit set forth for cad\nparticular model, there will be\nno congestion, and motorists\nconsequently will face no inon\nveniene.\nThe Inspection Division at the\nsame time announced the in\nspection lane schedules for the\nfirst three months of 1949.\nLAND SURVEYING\nWORK GUARANTEED\nD. C. Shearin\nRegistered Surveyor\nPHONE R-7014\nEnfield Woman\nWins Newspaper\nAuto Contest\nEnfield Mrs. William M.\nFowlkes of Enfield received a\nnew Oldsmobile sedan for\nChristmas as the first place\nprize in a subscription contest\nsponsored by the Enfield Prog\nress and Scotland Neck Com\nmonwealth weekly newspapers.\nMrs. Fowlkes received her\nnew automobile on Christmas\nDay after the contest had closed\nat noon on Christmas Eve after\nseveral weeks of spirited com\npetition in which those partici\npating were awarded a certain\nnumber of points for varying\nlengths of subscriptions and the\nhighest number of points won\nthe car.\nA second place award of $500\nin cash in Enfield and in Scot\nland Neck was given by the pa\npers, with B. B. Kimball of En\nfield as one of the winners and\nMrs. Lovegrove as the winner in\nScotland Neck.\nEric Rodgers of Scotland\nNeck is publisher of the two\nHalifax County weekly newspa\npers conducting the contest. A\nnumber of lesser awards were\nmade to residents in the two\ncommunities in the circulation\ncontest.\nTOWN TALK\nMiss Mary Lela Saunders of\nDanville. Virginia spent Sunday\nin the home of Mr. and Mrs.\nJim Ingram.\n_\nMr. and Mrs. Marion Saun\nders and daughter, Marion o f\nDanville spent the holidays with\nMr. and Mrs. W. S. Saunders.\nMrs. J. W. Gibson of Norfolk\nvisited with Mr. and Mrs. H. M.\nHudson.\nMisses Betty Wynn Ingram\nand Mary Lela Saunders and\nHarry \u201cFuzzy\u201d Weathers and\nBill Hodges spent Monday in\nRichmond, Virginia.\nMr. and Mrs. John Bounds\nj and son, Freeman of Richmond\nspent the holidays with Mr. and\nI Mrs. S. J. Bounds.\n_\nj Miss Elizabeth Faison of\nPortsmouth visited with Mr. and\nMrs. W. G. Bunch.\n1 Wayland \u201cDoc\u201d Jones visited\nwith his family in Blackstone ov\ner the holidays.\nShirley Draper, student nurse\nat Rex Hospital, Raleigh, spent\nChristmas day with her parents\nMr. and Mrs. Terry Draper, and\nsmall brother, Billy.\n^\u25a0up'sM\nLook ol rout\nSoot OTory\ndy cloo dead\n\na call lot and\ndallTOi\nPhono R-SI71\nAMERICAN\nShoe Shop\n(23 ROANOKE AVE.\nROANOKE RAPID!\n'these R-526\u2014nr R-M21\nMinimum Chug* 10*\nTimes l 3 b 12\nID Words -60 1.10 1.60 2.88\nU Words .00 1.1* 1.70 3.04\n12 Words .00 1.20 1.80 3.24\n13 Words M. 1.25 19. 3.42\n14 Words .00 1.30 2.00 3.60\n15 Words .80 1.35 2.10 3.73\nL 16 Words .60 1.40 2.20 3 96\nP 17 Words .60 1.45 2.30 4.14\n18 Words .00 1.50 2.40 4.32\n19 Words .60 1 55 2.50 4.50\n20 Words .60 1.60 2.60 4.r8\n21 Words .63 1.58 2.73 4.93\n22 Words .66 1.76 2.86 5.15\n23 Words .69 1.84 2.99 5.38\n24 Words .72 1.92 3.12 5.62\n25 Words .75 2.00 3.75 j.85\n26 Wordr .78 2.08 3.38 6.09\n27 Words .81 2.16 3.51 6 32\n28 Word